### 1.2 Network Topology & Failure Domain

**Topology (Locked):**

- Single physical Ethernet switch
- Proxmox host, Docker VM, TrueNAS VM, Synology NAS, and PBS Mini PC connected to the SAME switch
- Wired Ethernet ONLY (no Wi-Fi, no powerline)

**Failure Domain:**

- Switch failure = **TOTAL SYSTEM OUTAGE**
- Proxmox host failure = **TOTAL STORAGE OUTAGE**

This is an **ACCEPTED and INTENTIONAL** design constraint.

---

### 1.3 Power Architecture (Static Design)

- APC UPS
- USB-connected to Proxmox host
- Proxmox acts as NUT MASTER
- Synology NAS acts as NUT SLAVE
- TrueNAS VM is gracefully shut down by Proxmox during power events

**Intended Shutdown Order (Design Intent):**

1. Application VMs shut down
2. TrueNAS VM shuts down
3. Synology NAS shuts down
4. Proxmox host shuts down LAST

---

### 1.4 Time & Identity Baseline

The following systems are **REQUIRED** to support NTP:

- Proxmox host
- TrueNAS VM
- Synology NAS
- Docker VM
- Proxmox Backup Server Mini PC

Time synchronization is **REQUIRED** for snapshot ordering, backup timestamps, restore correctness, and authentication and TLS validity.

---

### 1.5 Virtualization Model

**VM 101 — TrueNAS (Storage Platform)**

- Runs the ZFS storage pool (RAID-Z2)
- Owns physical HDDs via LSI SAS HBA passthrough
- Stores all PBS backup archives for Proxmox, Debian VM, TrueNAS VM, and other VMs
- Maintains local ZFS snapshot history

**VM 102 — Docker Host**

- OS: Debian 12
- Runs: Docker, Applications (Nextcloud, Immich, Paperless), PostgreSQL, Redis
- Container volumes hosted on dedicated NVMe partition (Samsung 990 PRO)
- Mounts TrueNAS via NFS to provide rclone with access to PBS backup archives for cloud upload

**Rules (Architectural):**

- Docker NEVER runs on the Proxmox host
- Applications NEVER run on the Synology NAS
- TrueNAS is the authoritative backup store — all PBS archives reside there
- The Docker VM is disposable and rebuildable

---

### 1.6 Storage Responsibility Matrix (Architectural Truth)

| Data Type | Location | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| User files | TrueNAS ZFS (RAID-Z2) | Authoritative storage |
| Application runtime data | NVMe partition (Samsung 990 PRO) | Primary runtime state |
| Container volumes (configs, DBs, caches) | NVMe partition (Samsung 990 PRO) | Local container runtime state |
| Local snapshots | TrueNAS ZFS | Point-in-time rollback |
| Backup replicas | Synology NAS | Secondary copy (daily) |
| VM configs/backups | PBS Mini PC | Compute recovery |
| Cloud backups | Filen (rclone crypt, via Debian VM) | Off-site disaster recovery |

If application state conflicts with storage state: **TrueNAS storage reality ALWAYS WINS.**

A maximum data-loss window of **24 hours** is ACCEPTED.

---

### 1.7 Data Transport Role (Design Contract)

TrueNAS NFS is mounted on the Debian VM for rclone to read PBS backup archives and upload them to Filen Cloud. It is **NOT** in the application runtime data path.

- **Primary IO path:** Applications → Docker VM → NVMe partition (Samsung 990 PRO)
- **Backup IO path:** TrueNAS → Replication → Synology NAS (daily) + PBS backup nightly
- **Off-site IO path:** TrueNAS (PBS archives) → NFS → Debian VM → rclone crypt → Filen Cloud

---

### 1.8 Cloud Role (Architectural Intent)

Filen Cloud is used as the off-site backup destination.

- BACKUP TARGET ONLY
- NEVER mounted live
- NEVER authoritative
- Does NOT participate in runtime operation
- Encrypted client-side before transmission via rclone crypt

---

### 1.9 Boot & Startup Assumptions

- Proxmox must boot before storage becomes available
- TrueNAS VM must boot before applications can operate
- Synology NAS may normally remain powered off except during replication cycles
- PBS Mini PC operates independently on its own schedule

> **Design Consequence:** Loss of the Proxmox host temporarily removes storage access. This is an intentional and accepted risk.

---

### 1.10 Explicit Non-Goals

This system is **NOT:**

- Highly available
- Redundant across nodes
- Multi-site
- Autonomous
- Zero-RPO

This system **IS:**

- Deterministic
- Recoverable
- Auditable
- Snapshot-protected
- Backup-replicated (local + cloud)
- Quiet when healthy
- **Loud when broken**

A maximum RPO of **24 hours** is an EXPLICIT DESIGN ACCEPTANCE.

