## Section 2 — Tier-0 Platform Integrity & System Authority (ROOT)

### Role of This Section (Absolute)

This section defines the **minimum integrity conditions** under which the system is permitted to operate at all. This section is the **ROOT OF AUTHORITY.**

- All other sections are subordinate.
- All other documents must comply.
- No component, service, or automation may override this section.

Tier-0 integrity is binary:

- **VERIFIED** → system may operate
- **NOT VERIFIED** → system must stop

If any rule in this section is violated or cannot be determined with certainty: backup outputs are untrustworthy, restore guarantees are void, `/var/run/backup_inhibit` MUST exist, and operator intervention is required.

> **UNKNOWN ≠ SAFE · DEGRADED ≠ ACCEPTABLE**

---

### 2.1 Tier-0 Authority Hierarchy (Non-Negotiable)

Tier-0 is satisfied only if **ALL** authorities below are verified. Failure or UNKNOWN state at any layer → **Tier-0 FAILED.**

**1) Power Authority**

The system requires a verified, current UPS power state. Tier-0 considers power FAILED if mains power status is unknown, stale, or battery-only, or if shutdown coordination cannot be guaranteed.

**2) Time Authority**

| Condition | State |
|---|---|
| NTP sync age > 15 minutes | DEGRADED |
| Clock drift > 5 seconds | FAILED (Tier-0 FAILED) |
| NTP unreachable > 30 minutes | FAILED (Tier-0 FAILED) |
| Unknown or unverifiable time | FAILED (Tier-0 FAILED) |

NTP Master: Proxmox host serves NTP to all VMs. All VMs **MUST** sync time FROM Proxmox, not from external NTP servers directly. Independent external sync breaks timestamp ordering across the infrastructure.

All systems must be simultaneously compliant. Partial compliance is NOT acceptable. UNKNOWN time state is treated as FAILED.

**3) Storage Authority**

Authoritative storage = TrueNAS ZFS pool. Primary storage integrity must be provable.

- Authoritative storage is ONLINE
- Redundancy is intact (RAID-Z2 healthy)
- No unresolved integrity errors
- Storage state is known and current

Capacity Authority (Hard Law):

| Capacity | State |
|---|---|
| < 70% | VERIFIED |
| 70–74% | DEGRADED |
| 75–84% | WARNING |
| ≥ 85% | CRITICAL (Tier-0 FAILED) |
| Unknown | Tier-0 FAILED |

**4) Data Plane Integrity**

Runtime data flow is strictly defined as: `Applications → Docker VM → TrueNAS ZFS`

- A single authoritative writable copy
- No split-brain writable paths
- No ambiguity in data ownership
- Synology NAS is never runtime storage
- Backup flow is one-way only

**5) Tier-0 Metadata & Recoverability**

- Host configuration backups
- Backup system configuration
- Replication definitions
- Secrets and credentials
- Restore procedures

**6) Monitoring Truth**

- External heartbeat
- Verified alert delivery path

Heartbeat exists only when Tier-0 is VERIFIED. Absence of signal = UNKNOWN = FAILED.

---

### 2.2 Tier-0 Enforcement Mechanism

Tier-0 failure or uncertainty is represented only by: `/var/run/backup_inhibit`

- Exists if Tier-0 is FAILED or UNKNOWN
- Must be respected by all automation
- Prevents backups and restores
- May only be cleared by explicit operator action

---

### 2.3–2.8 Runtime Authority, Restore, Cloud, Taxonomy, Failure Assertion, Final Rule

These sub-sections are unchanged from the baseline document. Tier-0 applies continuously. If Tier-0 transitions from VERIFIED to FAILED: backups stop, replication stops, restores are forbidden, operator intervention is required.

The system must **fail closed, not degrade silently.** A maximum RPO of 24 hours is explicitly accepted. Tier-0 protects integrity, not continuity.

