## Section 5 — Docker VM

**Role: Application Runtime & Data Plane**

> ■ **STORAGE LAYOUT UPDATED**

Docker container persistent volumes and all application runtime data are hosted on a dedicated partition of the Samsung 990 PRO NVMe SSD. TrueNAS is mounted via NFS for rclone cloud upload purposes only — it is the backup store, not the runtime data source. Large personal files (movies etc.) stored directly on TrueNAS are accessed on-demand, not at runtime.

### 5.0 Architectural Role (Locked)

The Docker VM is the application execution environment. It is the only location where application workloads execute, application-level services run, and runtime behavior is produced. It **implements behavior but does not grant authority.**

### 5.2 Data Authority & Storage Boundary

| Storage | Contents | Authority |
|---|---|---|
| TrueNAS ZFS | PBS backup archives, logs, large personal files | AUTHORITATIVE (backup store) |
| NVMe Partition | Container volumes, app data, DBs, caches | PRIMARY runtime data store |
| Synology NAS | Backup copies only | Non-authoritative |

Databases derive meaning from filesystem content, not the reverse. If conflict exists: **Filesystem truth always wins.**

### 5.3–5.10 Storage Segmentation, Database, Data Plane, Execution, Update, Failure, Tier-0

All authority rules unchanged. The Docker VM is fully disposable and rebuildable. Rebuild must always realign to filesystem truth, not database state.

The Docker VM is:
- a runtime executor
- a behavior engine
- a disposable compute layer

The Docker VM is NOT:
- a storage authority
- a safety authority
- a recovery authority

**Integrity always overrides availability.**

